<subSubSection box="[199,1050,836,861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,401,1149]" box="[199,1050,836,861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,836,861]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new generic name alluded to its bent fore tibiae. Feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="565" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,401,1149]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,872,897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new genus and four closely related genera (
<taxonomicName authority="Cai &amp; Tomokuni 2003" authorityName="Cai &amp; Tomokuni" authorityYear="2003" box="[883,1273,872,897]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Camptibia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[883,1001,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">Camptibia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cai" box="[1010,1273,872,897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" refString="Cai, W. &amp; Tomokuni, M. (2003) Camptibia obscura, gen. et sp. nov. (Heteroptera: Reduviidae: Harpactorinae) from China. European Journal of Entomology, 100, 181 - 185. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.14411 / eje. 2003.028" type="journal article" year="2003">
Cai &amp; Tomokuni 
<number box="[1214,1273,872,896]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Stal 1861" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Rihirbus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1287,1384,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">Rihirbus</emphasis>
Stål 
<number box="[151,209,908,933]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" value="1861.0">1861</number>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[222,342,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">Brassivola</emphasis>
Distant 
<number box="[439,497,909,933]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" value="1904.0">1904</number>
, 
<emphasis box="[510,597,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">Agyrius</emphasis>
Stål 
<number box="[656,713,908,933]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" value="1863.0">1863</number>
) have some common morphological characters in fore legs: the apical part of fore tibia is bent (
<figureCitation box="[510,646,944,969]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 16. 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[284,1287,211,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[284,1302,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 16. 11. Camptibia obscura Cai &amp; Tomokuni; 12. Rihirbus sinicus Hsiao &amp; Ren; 13. Brassivola hystrix Distant; 14. Flexitibia orientalis sp. nov.; 15. Agyrius watanabeorum Ishikawa; 16. Endochus cingalensis Stål. 11 – 16, fore leg. 11 – 16, lateral view. Scale bar of 11 – 13, 16 = 2.00 mm; of 14 – 15 = 1.33 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230498/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">
Figs. 
<number box="[574,646,944,969]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" value="13.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="11.0">11–15</number>
</figureCitation>
), the apex of fore tibia with a small tubercle (
<figureCitation box="[1166,1303,944,969]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 16. 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[284,1287,211,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[284,1302,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 16. 11. Camptibia obscura Cai &amp; Tomokuni; 12. Rihirbus sinicus Hsiao &amp; Ren; 13. Brassivola hystrix Distant; 14. Flexitibia orientalis sp. nov.; 15. Agyrius watanabeorum Ishikawa; 16. Endochus cingalensis Stål. 11 – 16, fore leg. 11 – 16, lateral view. Scale bar of 11 – 13, 16 = 2.00 mm; of 14 – 15 = 1.33 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230498/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">
Figs. 
<number box="[1231,1303,944,968]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" value="12.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="11.0">11–14</number>
</figureCitation>
). But in the new genus, the anterior pronotal lobe is distinctly shorter than 
<number box="[884,894,981,1005]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[905,921,981,1005]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" value="2.0">2</number>
of posterior lobe, the pronotum is medianly discally feebly bulging and anteriorly declining, the femur apically with a pair of spines (vs. in the closely related genera, the anterior pronotal lobe is much larger, and the pronotum is distinctly transversely constricted and not bulging in middle, femur apically without a pair of spines (
<figureCitation box="[805,979,1088,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 16. 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1952,1975]" captionTargetBox="[284,1287,211,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[284,1302,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 16. 11. Camptibia obscura Cai &amp; Tomokuni; 12. Rihirbus sinicus Hsiao &amp; Ren; 13. Brassivola hystrix Distant; 14. Flexitibia orientalis sp. nov.; 15. Agyrius watanabeorum Ishikawa; 16. Endochus cingalensis Stål. 11 – 16, fore leg. 11 – 16, lateral view. Scale bar of 11 – 13, 16 = 2.00 mm; of 14 – 15 = 1.33 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230498/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="565">
Figs. 
<number box="[867,893,1088,1112]" pageId="1" pageNumber="565" value="11.0">11</number>
–13, 15
</figureCitation>
)). The genera morphologically related to the new genus can be separated using the following key.
</paragraph>
